Required parts

please refer to the BoM in the Github repository

Front
  • use 4 M3 screws and nuts for each speaker
  • cut 2 pair of common bi-polar electric wire and solder a pair to each speaker
  • press-fit the LED matrix in place, it should be tight enough to hold it without glue
  • fit the other extremity of the pair of speaker cables to the ADAFRUIT I2S 3W STEREO SPEAKER BONNET
  • wire the VCC (5V), GND, SDA and SDL pins from the LED Matrix to the corresponding labeled pins on the ADAFRUIT I2S 3W STEREO SPEAKER BONNET
Rear
  • secure the Raspberry Pi 3 Model B using 4 short wood screws (or some hot glue, really)
  • attach the ADAFRUIT I2S 3W STEREO SPEAKER BONNET to the Raspberry Pi
  • make the power cable pass through the hole and attach it to the Raspberry Pi
  • place 6 M3 nuts in the slots
Attaching front and rear

Just attach the 2 pieces and use 6 M3 screws (10 to 15 mm long) to secure the assembly

This free download includes the 3D printable files for an open-source (OS) version of the popular Everyman begleri. Aroundsquare is making this design available for free to the community as part of, in the continued efforts to help grow the begleri community and put good quality, high performance begleri in the hands of as many players as possible. The download is a zipped folder containing .stl and .dwg files, which should serve the purposes of most 3D print hobbiests, and should be workable for any go to 3D print shop. The Titan casings are designed to house up to two 5/16 inch hex nuts, and to accommodate the same 275 paracord used in the original Everymans (you may need to re-drill the holes to fit the cord through). Print outs will vary, and if your first print feels a bit tight for the hex nuts, upsize it by 5% or so.

In February 2017, Aroundsquare introduced the Everyman begleri, with an innovative new bead design drawing on key characteristics of the popular Titan and Hydra series. The Everyman series, along with the Titans and Hydras, have already become established as well-known reference standards against which other begleri are compared, and is available in a variety of weights and materials, with configurable internals. Aroundsquare is proud to now make this same basic design freely available for players and enthusiasts to print or adapt for their own use. The design has been adjusted slightly in both size and shape to make it suitable for commonly available 3D printing materials, and to make it relatively straightforward to print. Many thanks, and a great deal of respect to Alexander German for his support in the development of the model and prototypes.

The Everyman OS design, like all AO2 content, is available under creative commons: CC-BY-SA. The file is also available over at Thingiverse if you don't want to enter billing info to download here.

Please share your creations with #ao2os to help us all see the creations and iterations as they come!

The airfoil wings start with a taper of .3mm so that should be good for a first layer height. Use as light of an infill as you can print well so that the wings are light. Set your wall thickness to .5mm so the main body doesn't need any infill to be solid (it is 1mm wide). I also updated this from the last one so that the tail height is the same as the cockpit so that the tail doesn't get melted when printing the last few layers repeatedly. Now it should alternate back and forth the whole time so you can print this even without fans.

...note that if you want one that flies look elsewhere still! I printed this and it doesn't fly. The airfoil wings do actually give it a noticeable lift but the tail doesn't keep it up. The body is also too weak to support the heavier wings. I pictured them being lighter with infill but 90% of the wings are shells and not infill anyways. I am thinking a PLA glider needs to be quite a bit larger in order to be aerodynamic or needs to be designed for fast flight speeds more like a jet shape/regular paper airplane shape. v3 to come sometime as one of those...

v1 - http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2255999
v3 - http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2262354

comments.text:
For stable flight, the tail-needs to have an angle of attack that is a few degrees less than the wings, i.e. it needs to generate negative lift.
This means that if the plane speeds up it pulls the tail down, increasing the lift from the wings and slowing the plane down.
Also for stability the plane needs to balance about 1/4 of the wing chord (width) back from the leading edge of the wing (i.e. add nose weight).
The tail-plane also needs to be quite a bit larger, the more so compared to the wings the smaller the model.
Finally, for lateral stability, the vertical fin needs to be much bigger and the wings need some dihedral.
Achieving these things in a one piece 3D printed part is difficult!

Instructions:
Some weeks ago I got the Silver Crest Vacuum sealer for about 35 euro in Lidl. It is as the name indicates, a vacuum packer and plastic sealer in one, meant for vegetables sealings. I am using it for vacuum sealing and compressing the composite (glass and epoxy) on the outside of my 3d print.. The model has to have its surface offset inwards with the distance of the intended composite thickness. (that is done for the file frontFoilLeft.stl)

1: Printing my left and right wing at about 70% infill and gluing it together,

2: cut out two pieces for each side of the wing such that they get diagonal directions of fibers overlapping.

3: paint one layer of epoxy out on the plastic shape, lay on a glass layer and soak additional epoxy on top, distributing epoxy untill soaking all glass thats over the shape.

4: repeat with all layers, both top and bottom of the wing.

5: very carefully put the whole thing inside the vacuum plastic bag ( I did not do so well) avoid any epoxy or glass on the sealing surfaces(inside of opening of the bag.

6: place bag in vacuum sealer, and arrange the bag such that it will fit while vacuuming, and not tare itself on corners and edges of the shape.

7: vacuum little by little (use the stop button, and arrange the bag along the way)
8: vacuum until the vacuum pump stops, press stop to avoid sealing, and do another few rounds like that to vacuum all extra air out.
9: you are done, now wait 10 min and check the bag for air tightness - in my case I had a bad seal both due to holes in the bag, and glass fiber and epoxy residue in the opening seal.
-One trick to avoid this could be to fold the edge inward while bringing the object into the bag, then it may stay clean before the sealing process.

description.text:
When building your own printer. You are always trying to upgrade your machine.
In my case i started with a 3d printed extruder. This one broke on me, so i made an upgrade with a MK8full metal one. During print testing with different materials i found out that even these extruders need some more power to push the filament.
So i invested in a geared extruder (Titan).
Meaning i have a lot of metal extruders lying around. So i created this upgrade kit, for the full metal extruder.

Testrun works out fine. You need to invert youre extruder in your firmware and re calibrate the filament settings. Mine needed to be doubled.

Sorry i was misinformed by the specs of the 625RS bearing. I used the bearings of a belt pulley spanner. The website gave me measerments of the spanner and not of the bearing.
So I measured the 625rs Bearing. This one has an 16 mm outer diameter and 5 mm thickness ( vs 22m outer & 7mm thick).
Comparing the bearing with the drawing and a printed extruder. I Think its possible to make this work for the 608RS Bearing. But you need to make some adjustments to the extruder base. The hole needs to be 2 mm deeper (no problem). The bearing hole needs to be enlaged, and will have a litlle gap at the side of the drivegear. I don't think this will give large structural issues. If you fear this, you can make the hole where the little gear (Nema) runs through, a little thighter. Make it a 16 mm diameter instead of the 22mm its now. This will have enough space to let gear spin freely.
The top needs to be adjusted to fit the 608RS Bearing as well. Don't think this gives structural problems.

description.text: I bought one of these Mail Alert flags: http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B004ECG9FA/ref=wms_ohs_product?ie=UTF8&psc=1 The idea is you mount it to the top of your mailbox and it pops up when mail is delivered so you know if something's waiting for you. It replaces the built-in flag like that on my mailbox that broke ages ago. The flag is metal, and prone to freezing closed in the winter. If it's up when it freezes, and someone goes to lower it, it bends, and this broke it. This flag is designed to hold onto the broken-off piece by a set screw, replacing the flag. For extra bonus functionality, it rotates the visible part of the flag so it's more visible from coming up the road towards the mailbox, rather than from right in front of the mailbox.

No supports necessary -- the "flat on one side" design makes for an easy, yet solid, print.  No special infill or anything either.  I used a raft to avoid curling, but heck, even if there were some curl, it'd work fine.  
You'll need a small set screw to put through the hole on the inside (yes, the inside, to help protect it from rust; there's plenty of room) after sliding it over the broken-off flange of the hinged part.  It's best to get that set screw in place before sliding the flag onto the flange.  
The large hole at the tip is for the string that hangs into the mailbox door.  See the pictures of it in place on the mailbox.

When the Dodge Challenger Hellcat was first revealed, one of the coolest details was the hollow driver's side headlight that feeds cool air directly into the airbox. I found out reading some forums that the same headlight assembly is used on all 2015+ Challengers, but the lower trims use a plastic plug insert instead of leaving the headlight open.

Keep in mind that engines get hot and cars are subject to varying weather conditions when selecting your material! I was able to use ABS plastic and was pleased with the firm fit in the headlight inlet.

description.text:
I built this filter holder to use with my Rokinon 14mm ultra wide angle lens on my APSC cameras.
Is buit in 5 parts. a semi cilinder that sorround the actual hood of the lens, to prevent reflection from behind in the filter, two actual filter guide (you must to glue this to the semi cilinder), and two litle pieces to hold the screw (headles). This works fine with an APSC camera. In full frame cause an ugly vigneting.
Warning. I made this again after breaking my old pringting, but in Blue PLA. i dont recomend using light o other color than black, because will cause reflections in your filter and a nasty artifact. i recoment sand the inner part, until no reflections can be seen.

i recomend test a few layers of the semi cilinder to adjust scale.
after that print the pieces, glue the filter slots to the main (for the wide side, centered) and add the bolt and nut. if you prefer, cut the head of the bolt, and add the plastic nobs.
Update(20160218): use sandpaper in the the interior for less reflections, use black or most dark plastics, minimize the filtered and traslucent light from the sides

Turn your 608 bearing Fidget Spinner into your very own gyroscope. Just snap it into the bearing, spin, and let go. You spinner will balance itself like a toy top using its angular momentum from rotating. It will even balance on your fingers if you are careful.

It works best with a spinner that has a large mass and needs to be spinning quickly.

How I Printed It

I turned the model on its side in my slicer and added support material under the overhang.

A slight modification done to the base by LuckyPunk.  It was pretty difficult to get the support the Ultimaker had put on the design off.  By putting this into Tinkercad I quickly hollowed it out a bit more to make it easier to print and then clean up.  
Three different versions are included.  We went with the 3rd for the print seen here.  The support easily snapped off after removing from the base.  It balances very well, especially with a bit of sticky put on the bottom.

Printed by an Ultimaker with Touching Base support at 0.06mm thickness and 50 mm/s speed.  
Removing is a bit hard due to the rounded surface.  The only thing that seemed to work was to get a very sharp knife under an edge to pry it up a bit, followed by the usual metal spatula.

description.text:
Modified Gimbal for SG90 Micro servos meant to hold a 6mm Laser module. The hole is a bit big, I secured my laser with hot melt. In fact, I secured a lot of this with hot melt. Don't judge me.

Paired with an arduino, it makes a fun cat toy.

The housing is meant to hold an 1100mah LiPo battery pack, A micro-usb charging board, and an arduino mini pro on a small breadboard. The battery door has a hole for a 16mm latching button as an activation switch.

It should be fairly straightforward if you're into this sort of thing. If there's interest, I can write up a full tutorial. Comment me if you'd like that! Remember to give your felines a toy they can catch after they play with this so that they get the joy of catching it.

Special Thanks to Deanasawr for his original gimbal upon which this is based, and without which there's no way I could have designed this. http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1809433

UPDATE 17-04-24: I realized I accidentally uploaded a version of the base that included meshmixer supports. I've replaced it with the base that has no default support. It should print with the only support needed being in the USB port hole - even that should be fine with bridging, you might just need to file it out a bit after.

I've re-included the meshmixer support version, in case it is helpful to anyone, but the file is clearly labeled with supports. You only need one battery housing, so don't waste filament and print both :-)

Wanhao

Printer:

Wanhao Duplicator i3 V2

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

.2

Infill:

15%

Notes:

Rotate the parts so they print sensibly. Servo-side down is generally best.

The housing is large, but should print with the only support being on the USB port hole. Set overhang threshhold to 60*. I used rafts with a 10mm margin as the first print started warping off the bed.

Do test-fits to make sure that you have your servos centered okay. You'll need to screw the arms onto the servos, then hot melt glue the arms into the gimbal.

I included sample Arduino Code.

You'll need a 5V source of power. This can either be an external adapter, or a battery connected to some kind of voltage regulator.

NOTE: BE CAREFUL. LITHIUM ION BATTERIES CAN AND DO CAUSE FIRES IF WIRED INCORRECTLY. YOU SHOULD BE COMFORTABLE WITH LITHIUM ION BATTERY CIRCUITRY BEFORE ATTEMPTING. THESE INSTRUCTIONS ARE TO BE FOLLOWED AT YOUR OWN RISK AND COME WITH NO WARRANTY EXPRESSED OR IMPLIED.

I used a LiPo battery:
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00J2QET64/

Connected to a charger board:
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B06XCXPY86/

Connected to a 5V boost converter:
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B01MRG9CNM/

I desoldered the USB connector and attached leads to use that one.

You can bus together the 5v and Ground lines using wire nuts, a small soldered or solderless breadboard.

I connected a latching button between the battery charging board output and the boost converter input to turn the thing on and off.

The 5v rail should go to the 5v input of the servos:
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00M8SR0ZK/

The 5v lead of the laser diode:
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B01ITK4PEO/

And the 5v input of the Arduino. I do not reccomend attempting to power the servos and laser from the 5v output of the arduino. It will in all likelihood overload the regulator on board the arduino. I measured total draw of 450ma under load.

The ground rail goes to the ground of the arduino, the servos, and the laser.

As written, the data line of one servo attaches to pin 9, and the other of pin 10.

You'll probably want to resolder the laser diode to some longer and thicker leads. I recommend silicone wire for the job, so that it has more flex to travel.
I took the existing very nice micro servo gimbal, removed one axis (I only needed two) and kludgily made a laser mount in tinkercad. I'm new at this. Stop judging me, I already warned you.

description.text:
This is a remix of the Quadrifilar Helix Antenna by @jhsandell for 1090MHz (ADS-B)

The following updates have been made:

  • The 'bug' that jhsandell noted where the code was using diameters rather than radii has been fixed
  • This version makes a left-handed helix for right-handed polarization, rather than a right-handed helix for left-handed polarization*
  • Settings have been adjusted for ADS-B frequencies (1090 MHz)

There are a variety of pros/cons for a QFH antenna for ADS-B:

Pros:

  • Using circular polarization, antenna is not sensitive to changes in aircraft orientation
  • Radiation pattern is more or less omni-directional around a single hemisphere (note that this would be in the direction of the feedpoint!)
  • Multi-path rejection
  • It's purty

Cons:

  • ADS-B is by standard vertically-polarized, so using a circularly-polarized antenna means a 3dB loss
  • Takes up significantly more space than a simple vertical or J-pole
  • Construction is more complicated than other antenna types, and care must be taken to attach the feedpoint properly

The wire used in the photographs is 10awg copper wire - this is equal to the 2.5mm wire diameter suggested by the calculator as an optimum for this frequency. However, for a smaller gauge might be recommended for easier construction.

*The photographs show a left-handed polarized (so right-handed helix), rather than the LHP version in the OpenSCAD file. For ADS-B, polarization-handedness is unimportant.

description.text:
The 30 Watt UV LED gets pretty warm and needs to be cooled so it will not burn out. The current models of the D7 appear to run warm after time and it is thought that the issue could be related to the way the cooling fan / hot-sink and airflow interact. The air is drawn in from the cooling opening in the base of the printer but the issue seems to be that there is a very large gap between the cool air entry and the actual cooling fan and heat sink. There is also no good hot air exit and the warm air inside can be circulated back into the fan instead of cool air.

See http://3dprinterwiki.info/wiki/wanhao-duplicator-d7-sla/tips-mods/uv-coolling-shroud/ for more instructions and photos.
